  <investigation xml:id="pa-inverse-variation-formula">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Suppose that the number of hours, <m>h</m>, required to build a fence is inversely proportional to the number of people, <m>n</m>, working on the fence.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If it takes <m>4</m> people <m>31</m> hours to build the fence, what is <m>c</m>, the constant of proportionality?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the definition of inverse proportionality and your constant of proportionality to write an equation that shows the relationship between <m>h</m> and <m>n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use your equation to predict how long it will take <m>11</m> people to build the fence.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use your equation to predict how many people need to be on the team in order to build the fence in 8 hours.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-compare-inverse-direct-variation">
    <statement>
        <p>
            You have now seen examples of quantities that vary directly/are proportional to each other and quantities that vary inversely/are inversely proportion to each other. How are proportional relationships and inversely proportional relationship similar? How are they different? 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </investigation>

  <investigation xml:id="pa-prep-survey-inverse-variation">
      <p>
          You'll need to be able to do the following things for this lesson. Rate how confident you are on a scale of 1 - 5 (1 = not confident and 5 = very confident).
      </p>
      <table>
          <tabular bottom = "minor" top = "minor" left = "minor" right = "minor">
              <row header ="yes" bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Skill or Concept: I can …</cell>
                  <cell>Rating from 1 to 5</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Find the constant of proportionality for two quantities with an inversely proportional relationship from data.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom = "minor">
                  <cell>Determine whether two quantities have an inversely proportional relationship.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                  <cell>Write an equation that shows a quantity <m>Q_2</m> varies inversely with respect to another quantity <m>Q_1</m>.</cell>
                  <cell></cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell>Compare and contrast inverse and direct variation.</cell>
                <cell></cell>
              </row>
          </tabular>
      </table>
  </investigation>
</section>